31    /**
32    * DateTime is the standard implementation of an unmodifiable datetime class.
33    * <p>
34    * <code>DateTime</code> is the most widely used implementation of
35    * {@link ReadableInstant}. As with all instants, it represents an exact
36    * point on the time-line, but limited to the precision of milliseconds.
37    * A <code>DateTime</code> calculates its fields with respect to a
38    * {@link DateTimeZone time zone}.
39    * <p>
40    * Internally, the class holds two pieces of data. Firstly, it holds the
41    * datetime as milliseconds from the Java epoch of 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z.
42    * Secondly, it holds a {@link Chronology} which determines how the
43    * millisecond instant value is converted into the date time fields.
44    * The default Chronology is {@link ISOChronology} which is the agreed
45    * international standard and compatible with the modern Gregorian calendar.
46    * <p>
47    * Each individual field can be queried in two ways:
48    * <ul>
49    * <li><code>getHourOfDay()</code>
50    * <li><code>hourOfDay().get()</code>
51    * </ul>
52    * The second technique also provides access to other useful methods on the
53    * field:
54    * <ul>
55    * <li>numeric value
56    * <li>text value
57    * <li>short text value
58    * <li>maximum/minimum values
59    * <li>add/subtract
60    * <li>set
61    * <li>rounding
62    * </ul>
63    * <p>
64    * DateTime is thread-safe and immutable, provided that the Chronology is as well.
65    * All standard Chronology classes supplied are thread-safe and immutable.
66    *
67    * @author Stephen Colebourne
68    * @author Kandarp Shah
69    * @author Brian S O'Neill
70    * @since 1.0
71    * @see MutableDateTime
72    */

224    /**
225    * Constructs an instance from an Object that represents a datetime.
226    * <p>
227    * If the object implies a chronology (such as GregorianCalendar does),
228    * then that chronology will be used. Otherwise, ISO default is used.
229    * Thus if a GregorianCalendar is passed in, the chronology used will

232    * The recognised object types are defined in

234    * include ReadableInstant, String, Calendar and Date.
235    * The String formats are described by {@link ISODateTimeFormat#dateTimeParser()}.
236    *

1214    /**
1215    * Returns a copy of this datetime with the specified period taken away.
1216    * <p>
1217    * This method will subtract each element of the period one by one, from
1218    * largest to smallest, adjusting the datetime to be accurate between each.
1219    * <p>
1220    * Thus, subtracting a period of one month and one day from 2007-05-31 will
1221    * work as follows:
1222    * First subtract one month and adjust, resulting in 2007-04-30
1223    * Then subtract one day and adjust, resulting in 2007-04-29.
1224    * Note that the day has been adjusted by two.
1225    * <p>
1226    * This method is typically used to subtract complex period instances.
1227    * Subtracting one field is best achieved using methods
1228    * like {@link #minusYears(int)}.
1229    * <p>
1230    * If the amount is zero or null, then <code>this</code> is returned.
1231    * This datetime instance is immutable and unaffected by this method call.
1232    *
1233    * @param period the period to reduce this instant by
1234    * @return a copy of this datetime with the period taken away
1235    * @throws ArithmeticException if the new datetime exceeds the capacity of a long
1236    */

2001    /**
2002    * DateTime.Property binds a DateTime to a DateTimeField allowing powerful
2003    * datetime functionality to be easily accessed.
2004    * <p>
2005    * The simplest use of this class is as an alternative get method, here used to
2006    * get the year '1972' (as an int) and the month 'December' (as a String).
2007    * <pre>
2008    * DateTime dt = new DateTime(1972, 12, 3, 0, 0, 0, 0);
2009    * int year = dt.year().get();
2010    * String monthStr = dt.month().getAsText();
2011    * </pre>
2012    * <p>
2013    * Methods are also provided that allow date modification. These return new instances
2014    * of DateTime - they do not modify the original. The example below yields two
2015    * independent immutable date objects 20 years apart.
2016    * <pre>
2017    * DateTime dt = new DateTime(1972, 12, 3, 0, 0, 0, 0);
2018    * DateTime dt20 = dt.year().addToCopy(20);
2019    * </pre>
2020    * Serious modification of dates (ie. more than just changing one or two fields)
2021    * should use the {@link org.joda.time.MutableDateTime MutableDateTime} class.
2022    * <p>
2023    * DateTime.Propery itself is thread-safe and immutable, as well as the
2024    * DateTime being operated on.
2025    *
2026    * @author Stephen Colebourne
2027    * @author Brian S O'Neill
2028    * @since 1.0
2029    */
